# Bring your own core or backend

This generated product can wrap existing first-party code without moving it
into the Resource Vault demo. Configure `APP_PRODUCT_ROUTERS` with one or more
Python import targets; their endpoints join this backend's OpenAPI schema,
typed frontend client, auth boundary, desktop transport and deployment.

## Existing FastAPI backend

Make the existing package a backend dependency, then point at an `APIRouter`,
router factory, or `FastAPI` app:

```bash
uv add --package {{ pkg_slug }}-backend --editable ../my-existing-backend

APP_PRODUCT_ROUTERS=my_backend.api:router
uv run {{ cli_name }} product check
uv run {{ cli_name }} dev
uv run {{ cli_name }} gen
```

An editable path outside the repo is convenient for development. For CI,
Docker and releases, include that dependency in the checkout/build context or
publish it to your package index.

Multiple targets are comma-separated. Prefer an `APIRouter` with paths under
`/api`. A full `FastAPI` app is accepted, but only its API endpoints are
imported; its middleware, lifespan, docs and static mounts remain its own and
are not merged into this host.

## Existing core package

Keep the core unchanged and add a thin HTTP adapter:

```python
# apps/backend/src/{{ pkg_slug }}_backend/product_adapter.py
from fastapi import APIRouter

from my_core import TaskService


def create_router() -> APIRouter:
    service = TaskService(...)  # wire your existing ports here
    router = APIRouter(prefix="/api/tasks", tags=["tasks"])

    @router.get("")
    def list_tasks():
        return service.list()

    return router
```

```bash
APP_PRODUCT_ROUTERS={{ pkg_slug }}_backend.product_adapter:create_router
uv run {{ cli_name }} product check
uv run {{ cli_name }} gen
```

Business rules stay in the core. The factory owns dependency construction and
the route owns HTTP translation. Once OpenAPI is regenerated, add thin React
hooks/views over the generated types; desktop and deployment require no
domain-specific changes.

Frozen desktop builds add the configured modules as PyInstaller hidden imports.
Build with the same `APP_PRODUCT_ROUTERS` value the packaged app will use.

## Pick the right seam

| Seam | Best for |
| --- | --- |
| `APP_PRODUCT_ROUTERS` | Existing first-party core/backend code |
| Plugin SDK | Optional or third-party extensions |
| `[demo]` replacement recipe | Building a new native domain across every adapter |
